NAME
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            cleanname - clean a path name

SYNOPSIS
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            cleanname \[ -d dir \] name ...

DESCRIPTION
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            Cleanname tidies up each file name it is given and prints
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            the result on standard output. It removes redundant slashes
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            and interprets ``.'' and ``..'' directory names lexically.
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            If the -d option is given, each name that does not not start
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            with / or # will be prefixed by dir/ before processing.

SOURCE
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            /appl/cmd/cleanname.b

SEE ALSO
<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>            <action name=basename(1)>basename(1)</action>, <action name=pwd(1)>pwd(1)</action>, <action name=names(2)>names(2)</action>

<style color=#00ffffff size=1>.</style>                                Inferno Manual
